div.p:
For the Apostles,
sensing themselves bound by a strict commandment
to announce the Gospel in the very manner
that Christ taught and commanded,
therefore observed most strictly,
in both word and deed,
the aforesaid form and manner in converting the world.
Concerning them,
Augustine in Letter 3 to Volusianus
says:
filled with the Holy Spirit,
they suddenly speak the languages of all nations;
they faithfully refute errors;
they preach most wholesome truth;
they exhort to repentance;
they promise, from divine grace,
pardon for past blameworthy life;
fitting signs and miracles follow upon the preaching of true and holy religion;
fierce unbelief is stirred up against them;
they endure what was foretold,
they hope for what was promised;
they teach what was commanded;
few in number they are scattered throughout the world;
they convert peoples with wondrous ease;
they grow in the midst of enemies;
they increase under persecutions;
through the narrow straits of afflictions
they spread to the very ends of the earth;
and further:
the temples and images of demons
and sacrilegious rites
are gradually and in turn overthrown,
as the prophets had foretold.
Thus Augustine.
